  * and provide the tools to identify the *types of bonds and forces that occur between molecules (no Wikipedia page)*.

### **Introduction and the Biochemistry of Life**

#### **Goals**

* Understand the basic components and forces found in [biological macromolecules](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Macromolecule).  
  * Understand that, despite their different levels of organization, all organisms are comprised of [cells](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell\_(biology)), the basic unit of life.![][image1]  
  * Recognize that a cell and its various sub-cellular structures are comprised of four major classes of macromolecules: [carbohydrates](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbohydrate), [lipids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lipid), [proteins](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protein), and nucleic acids.  
    ![][image2]  
    Protein Myoglobin

![][image3] Nucleic acids RNA (left) and DNA (right).

* Understand the general structure of [lipids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lipid) and [phospholipids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phospholipid) and how this structure dictates function.  
  * Understand the general structure of simple and complex carbohydrate molecules and how this structure dictates function.  
  * Understand the general structure of [ATP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adenosine\_triphosphate).

![][image4]

Adenosine triphosphate (ATP)

#### **Objectives**

At the end of this learning sequence, you should be able to...

* List the most common elements found in [biological macromolecules](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covalent\_bond) and describe the properties of these [atoms](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atom).  
  * Describe [electronegativity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronegativity) and [electron affinity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electron\_affinity).  
  * Predict the effects of electronegativity and electron affinity on molecular interactions.  
  * Identify the [types of bonds](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical\_bond) or forces between different interacting groups.  
  * Explain how [hydrogen bonds](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrogen\_bond) are formed.

![][image5]  
Model of hydrogen bonds (1) between molecules of water

* List examples of the importance of hydrogen bonds in biological systems.  
  * Design molecules with particular properties that can form a specific type of bond.  
  * Describe the role that [phospholipids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phospholipid) and [carbohydrates](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbohydrate) have in a [cell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell\_(biology)).  
  * Describe how the basic components and forces dictate the structure and function of [phospholipids](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phospholipid) and [carbohydrates](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbohydrate).  
  * Identify the basic building blocks of [membranes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Membrane), [carbohydrates](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbohydrate), and [proteins](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protein).  
    ![][image6]  
    Schematic of size-based membrane exclusion  
  * Draw the basic building blocks of [membranes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Membrane) and [carbohydrates](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbohydrate).  
  * Explain why [ATP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adenosine\_triphosphate) is a high-energy molecule that powers cellular work.
